sec.p:
Cyrtodactylus Gray
is the most species-rich genus of gekkonid lizards, comprising of 307 described species (Uetz et al. 2021; Mirza et al. 2021). The members of the genus are distributed throughout Southeast Asia (
Grismer et al. 2018a
;
Riyanto et al. 2018
); South Asia ( Annandale 1913 ;
Agarwal et al. 2018a
); northern Australia , New Guinea , and the Solomon Islands (
Davis et al. 2019
;
Wood et al. 2012
). The Indo-Burma region is represented by about 27 species, of which nine species are known from the northeast Indian states (
Agarwal et al . 2018a
,b;
Purkayastha et al. 2020a
) namely C. guwahatiensis Agarwal, Mahony, Giri, Chaitanya & Bauer
( Assam ); C. jaintiaensis Agarwal, Mahony, Giri, Chaitanya & Bauer
( Meghalaya ); C. kazirangaensis Agarwal, Mahony, Giri, Chaitanya & Bauer
( Assam ); C. khasiensis (Jerdon)
(Historically reported from throughout northeast India but is known with certainty only from East Khasi Hills district, Meghalaya ; see
Agarwal et al 2018b
); C. montanus Agarwal, Mahony, Giri, Chaitanya & Bauer
( Tripura and Mizoram ); C. nagalandensis Agarwal, Mahony, Giri, Chaitanya & Bauer
( Nagaland ); C. septentrionalis Agarwal, Mahony, Giri, Chaitanya & Bauer
( Assam ); C. tripuraensis Agarwal, Mahony, Giri, Chaitanya & Bauer
( Tripura ) and C. urbanus Purkayastha, Das, Bohra, Bauer & Agarwal
( Assam and Meghalaya ). Until recently, northeast India was known to have a single species of Cyrtodactylus , C. khasiensis and the rest of the eight species reported from northeast India have been described since 2018. Cyrtodactylus khasiensis is rather a species group (
Purkayastha et al . 2020a
) consisting of superficially similar but genetically distinct species (see
Agarwal et al . 2018a
, 2018b ;
Purkayastha et al . 2020a
). The Brahmaputra River system has been perceived as a barrier giving rise to the “south of Brahmaputra clade” which again is further divided into lowland and highland clades (
Agarwal et al . 2018b
). In this paper we describe four new species in the “south of Brahmaputra clade” with two species in the lowland clade from Siju ( 25.356832°N , 90.693271°E ) in the South Garo Hills District in the state of Meghalaya and two species in the highland clade from Aizawl city area ( 23.730°N , 92.718°E ), Tamdil National Wetland ( 23.442°N , 92.571°E ) and Sailam village ( 23.350371°N , 92.797582°E ), Mizoram state of northeast India .

The following measurements and meristics were recorded, abbreviations and terminology are as follows: 
SVL
, snout to vent length; 
TRL
, trunk length; BW, maximum body width; TL, tail length; TW, tail width taken on first tail segment; TD, tail depth taken on first tail segment; HL, head length from the snout tip to the retroarticular process of the jaw; HW, maximum head width; JW, jaw width taken ventrally at the retroarticular process of the jaw; HD, maximum head depth; FL, forearm length; CL, crus length; OD, orbit diameter; NO, distance between the posterior edge of the nostril and the anterior orbital border; SO, distance between the snout tip and the anterior orbital border; OE, distance between posterior orbital border and the anterior border of the ear; EL, maximum ear length; ES, anterior border of the ear to the snout tip; IN, internarial distance; IO, minimum interorbital distance between left and right supraciliary rows; FW, minimum frontal width; RL, maximum rostral length; RW, maximum rostral width; 
ML
, maximum mental length; 
MW
, maximum mental width; 
PMIL
, maximum length of inner postmental; 
PMIIL
, maximum length of outer postmental; digits were measured from the proximal apex with the neighbouring digit to the tip (excluding the claw), and numbered from inner (I) to outer (
V
) as follows: on manus, FIL, FIIL, FIIIL, FIVL, FVL; on pes, TIL, TIIL, TIIIL, TIVL, TVL; PcP, precloacal pores; PcFP, precloacofemoral pores; 
MVSR
, mid-ventral scale rows (counted between ventrolateral folds); PVT, paravertebral tubercles on the trunk only (counted between the level of the axilla and the level of the groin); 
DTR
, dorsal tubercle rows (counted transversely across the body); SL, total supralabials; IL, total infralabials. Two separate series for subdigital lamellae were counted on all digits of the right manus and right pes, a basal series, that includes scales of a width at least twice the diameter of palmar scales up to and including a single large scale at the digital inflection, and an apical series, including lamellae distal to the digital inflection and not including the ventral claw sheath or nonlamellar scales between the basal and apical lamellae series (counted separately), abbreviated as follows: on manus, FILam, FIILam, FIIILam, FIVLam, FVLam; on pes, TILam, TIILam, TIIILam, TIVLam, TVLam.

Newly described species are compared morphologically with all known species from the khasiensis group (
Agarwal et al . 2014
) and other species from northeast India and surrounding countries. Comparisons were made through examination of type specimens (see Appendix I), literature containing original descriptions and literature reviewing a species based on type specimens (i.e., Bauer 2003 ;
Darevsky et al. 1998
;
Agarwal et al. 2018b
, 2018c ; Li 2007 ; Mahony 2009 ;
Purkayastha et al. 2020a
; Mirza et al . 2021).

Molecular data. For this study, eight specimens of Cyrtodactylus were sequenced. Genomic DNA was extracted from ethanol (100%) preserved liver tissue using Tissue Kit (Qiagen) following manufacturer’s instructions. Sequences were generated using the primer pair MetF1 and H5934 (
Macey et al. 1997
, 989 nucleotides). Sequencing was carried out by Eurofins Scientific and Barcode Bioscience. Sequence chromatograms were quality checked, edited and assembled into contigs using Sequence Scanner v1.0 (Applied Biosystems). Comparative ND2 sequences comprising Indo-Burma clade members of Cyrtodactylus were obtained from GenBank (
Siler et al. 2010
;
Wood et al. 2012
;
Agarwal et al. 2014
, 2018c ;
Grismer et al. 2018a
, 2018b , 2019;
Purkayastha et al . 2020a
; (Appendix II). Sequence alignment was done using MUSCLE ( Edgar 2004 ) in MEGA7 ( Tamura & Nei 1993 ;
Kumar et al. 2016
) with default parameter settings. Phylogenetic relationships were estimated with Maximum Likelihood ( ML ) in RaxmlGUIv1.3 ( Silvestro & Michalak 2012 ) using the GTR+gamma model with 1000 rapid bootstraps. Uncorrected pairwise sequence divergence was calculated in MEGA7.

We uncovered four distinct populations of Cyrtodactylus , two each from the states of Meghalaya and Mizoram , India (
). The Cyrtodactylus addressed in this study from Siju, South Garo Hills, were found to be the members of the lowland clade within the “south of Brahmaputra clade.” Two distinct populations were identified, differing from each other in ND2 gene sequence with an uncorrected p-distance of 0.065 ( Table 1 ). Individuals of the two clades were living in sympatry. Collectively, the “Siju” populations were recovered as sister taxa to Cyrtodactylus septentrionalis (
).

