sec.p:
The two northeast Indian states, Meghalaya and Mizoram are part of the north-western extremity of the Indo-Burma biodiversity hotspot. Given its high diversity of landforms and climatic zones, Indo-Burma harbours relatively large arrays of habitat and biodiversity. The high level of endemism and diversity is also contributed to by the hotspot’s geological and evolutionary history (
Tordoff et al . 2012
). With detailed evaluation of the C. khasiensis group (see Agarwal 2018b ) more species have been uncovered, most of which are morphologically similar.

Both the new species of Cyrtodactylus from Siju, Meghalaya show a relatively smaller genetic divergence (6.5% of divergence in ND2 sequence). But being sympatric species and differing in important morphological characters including orientation and number of PcP/PcFP in males suffices for considering both the groups as distinct taxa. Since the secretion from the glands in precloacal and/or femoral region influences the reproductive behiviour (
Chamut et al. 2009
,
Colosimo et al. 2020
), this parameter is important in context of segregation of species. Furthermore, many species within the genus Cyrtodactylus are considered distinct species with lesser genetic divergence (2.3%–6.1%) but presenting diverse morphological features (see
Grismer et al. 2020a
;
Schneider et al. 2020
).

Interestingly, both the species were from limestone cave habitat highlighting the unique biogeography and steep terrain often associated with limestone areas has resulted in the evolution of specialised karst endemic biodiversity. New species are regularly uncovered in these karst habitats in Southeast Asia (e.g.,
Grismer et al . 2017
; 2018a , 2020). In contrast the karst landscape of northeast India is still relatively under-explored in terms of herpetofauna. Limestone from Meghalaya state is a major raw material used in the cement industry in India , and currently almost all of the major cement plants operating in northeast India are located in Meghalaya ( Lamare & Singh 2016 ). Limestone is the second most extracted resource after coal in Meghalaya , with a reported 14,959 million tonnes of cement-grade limestone reserve in the state, accounting for around 9% of the total Indian reserve ( Lamare & Singh 2016 ). Large scale commercial and unregulated private mining activities are amongst of leaing causes of deforestation in Meghalaya state ( Lele & Joshi 2009 ; Lemare & Singh 2016), and so may contribute to the loss of many endemic and threatened species along with species still unknown to science. Siju being a limestone area with a number of limestone caves is also vulnerable in terms of limestone mining. Limestone karst habitats are extraordinary landscapes for specialised organisms and supports distinctive vegetation formations, with high levels of massif-specific endemism, particularly among plants, reptiles and molluscs (
Tordoff et al . 2012
). Lizards found in these places are often unique in their adaptations ( Nielsen & Oliver 2017 ). Cyrtodactylus have evolved to adapt to rocky-granite and limestone habitats (
Grismer et al. 2018a
). The ongoing discovery of new species of Cyrtodactylus from Southeast Asia mostly from karst habitats demonstrates the importance of the habitat for the evolution of this group of geckos and contributes to make it the most diversified group of geckos ( Bauer 2003 ;
Grismer et al . 2017
;
Agarwal et al. 2014
;
Agarwal et al . 2018a
, 2018b , 2018c ;
Murdoch et al . 2019
). The description of fifteen new species of Cyrtodactylus (
Grismer et al . 2017
;
Grismer et al . 2018a
) from the Shan Plateau and Salween Basin and six species from Cardamom Mountains and other portions of Southeast Asia (
Murdoch et al . 2019
) within a span of three years demonstrates that Southeast Asia is a hotspot for speciation of Cyrtodactylus in karstic habitats. However, similar endemism and specialisation has also been reported from the karstic habitat of New Guinea ( Nielsen & Oliver 2017 ).

For the state of Mizoram , recent studies have resulted in the discovery of new amphibian and reptilian species (e.g.
Sengupta et al . 2010
;
Vogel et al . 2017
;
Giri et al . 2019a
, 2019b ;
Vogel et al . 2020
) and distributional range extensions (e.g.
Sailo et al . 2009
;
Lalremsanga et al . 2010
; Lalremsanga 2017a , 2017b , 2017c ;
Lalremsanga et al . 2018a
, 2018b ; Ashaharazza et al . 2019; Lalbiakzuala & Lalremsanga 2019b , 2019c ;
Decemson et al . 2020
;
Hmar et al . 2020
;
Kundu et al. 2020
;
Lalremsanga et al . 2020
;
Malsawmhriatzuali et al. 2020
; Muansanga 2020;
Muansanga et al . 2020a
, 2020b ). Until this study, only two species of Bent-toed geckos, C. khasiensis ( Mathew 2007 )
and C. montanus (
Muansanga et al . 2020a
)
were recorded from Mizoram state . In the present study, collected individuals in the same habitat were represented by a single species. The distribution of C. aaronbraueri is limited to the Aizawl city area and Tamdil National Wetland in the northern belt of Mizoram , while C. bengkhuaiai is solely confined to the hill arrays of Sailam in the central part of the state. Furthermore, we suggest that the earlier record of C. khasiensis from Mizoram based on the specimen from unspecified site located 2 km from Sainik rest house in Lunglei town, Lunglei district (VR/ERS/ZSI/251), and another from Kolasib Agriculture IB compound, Kolasib district (VR/ERS/ZSI/252) ( Mathew 2007 ) require reinvestigation. Although C. khasiensis sensu stricto has been reported from Mizoram , the occurrence of such range-restricted species (see Agarwal 2018b ) from Mizoram is unlikely and may be a case of mistaken identity. Thus, we recommend removing the species C. khasiensis from the faunal inventories of the Mizoram state .
